{"title_page": "Mario Monti", "text_new": "{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2013}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[Senator for life]]\n|name             = Mario Monti\n|honorific-suffix = {{small|[[Order of Merit of the Italian Republic|OMRI]]}}\n|image            = Mario Monti - Festival Economia 2013 (cropped 2).JPG\n|office1          = 54th [[Prime Minister of Italy]]\n|president1       = [[Giorgio Napolitano]]\n|term_start1      = 16 November 2011\n|term_end1        = 28 April 2013\n|predecessor1     = [[Silvio Berlusconi]]\n|successor1       = [[Enrico Letta]]\n|office2          = [[List of Italian Ministers of Economy and Finances|Minister of Economy and Finances]]\n|term_start2      = 16 November 2011\n|term_end2        = 11 July 2012\n|primeminister2   = ''Himself''\n|predecessor2     = [[Giulio Tremonti]]\n|successor2       = [[Vittorio Grilli]]\n|office3          = [[European Commissioner for Competition]]\n|president3       = [[Romano Prodi]]\n|term_start3      = 15 September 1999\n|term_end3        = 30 October 2004\n|predecessor3     = [[Karel Van Miert]]\n|successor3       = [[Neelie Kroes]]\n|office4          = [[European Commissioner for Internal Market and Services|European Commissioner for Internal Market, Services]], [[European Commissioner for Taxation and Customs Union, Audit and Anti-Fraud|Customs and Taxation]]\n|president4       = [[Jacques Santer]]\n|term_start4      = 18 January 1995\n|term_end4        = 15 September 1999\n|predecessor4     = [[Raniero Vanni d'Archirafi]]\n|successor4       = [[Frits Bolkestein]]\n|office5         = President of the [[Bocconi University]]\n|term_start5  = 1994\n|term_end5    =\n|predecessor5 = [[Giovanni Spadolini]]\n|office6          = [[Senator for Life]]\n|term_start6      = 9 November 2011\n|term_end6        =\n\n|birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1943|3|19|df=y}}\n|birth_place      = [[Varese]], [[Lombardy]], [[Kingdom of Italy]]\n|party            = [[Independent politician|Independent]] {{nowrap|{{small|(1995\u20132013; 2015\u2013present)}}}}<br />[[Civic Choice]] {{small|(2013\u201315)}}\n|spouse           = {{Marriage|Elsa Antonioli|1970}}\n|children         = 2\n|alma_mater       = [[Bocconi University]]<br />[[Yale School of Management|Yale University]]\n|signature        = Mario Monti signature.svg\n}}\n{{Mario Monti sidebar}}\n'''Mario Monti''', {{post-nominals|post-noms=[[Order of Merit of the Italian Republic|OMRI]]}} (born 19 March 1943) is an Italian [[economist]] who served as the [[Prime Minister of Italy]] from 2011 to 2013, despite never having been an elected politician, leading a [[government]] of [[technocrat]]s in the wake of the [[European sovereign-debt crisis#Italy|Italian debt crisis]].\n\nMonti served as a [[European Commissioner]] from 1995 to 2004, with responsibility for the [[European Commissioner for Internal Market and Services|Internal Market, Services]], [[European Commissioner for Taxation and Customs Union, Audit and Anti-Fraud|Customs and Taxation]] from 1995 to 1999 and for [[European Commissioner for Competition|Competition]] from 1999 to 2004. Monti has also been Rector and President of [[Bocconi University]] in [[Milan]] for many years. On 12 November 2011, in the midst of the [[European sovereign debt crisis]], Monti was invited by [[President of Italy|President]] [[Giorgio Napolitano]] to form a new technocratic government following the [[resignation of Silvio Berlusconi]]. Monti was sworn in as Prime Minister on 16 November 2011, just a week after having been appointed a [[Senator for life|Senator for Life]] by President Napolitano, and initially became [[List of Italian Ministers of Economy and Finances|Minister of Economy and Finances]] as well, giving that portfolio up the following July. From 16 May 2013 to 17 October 2013 Monti was the President of [[Civic Choice]], a [[Centrism|centrist]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parties-and-elections.eu/italy.html|title=Parties and Elections in Europe|author=Wolfram Nordsieck|work=parties-and-elections.eu}}</ref> [[List of political parties in Italy|political party]].\n\n==Early life==\nMonti was born in [[Varese]] on 19 March 1943.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mario Monti nominato senatore a vita&nbsp;\u2014 La mossa del Colle, il via libera del premier|url=http://www.repubblica.it/politica/2011/11/09/news/mario_monti_nominato_senatore_a_vita_la_mossa_del_colle_nei_giorni_della_crisi-24745975/|accessdate=14 November 2011|newspaper=La Repubblica|date=9 November 2011|language=Italian}}</ref> His mother was from [[Piacenza]]. Although his father grew up in Varese, he was born in [[Luj\u00e1n, Buenos Aires Province|Luj\u00e1n]] in the [[Buenos Aires Province]], [[Argentina]], where his grandfather Abramo had [[Italian Argentine|emigrated]] to from [[Italy]] in the 19th century and built up a soft-drink and beer-production business.<ref>[http://angelodaddesio.nova100.ilsole24ore.com/2011/11/monti-ditalia-e-dargentina.html \"''Monti d'Italia e d'Argentina \u2013 Il Grande Sud''\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120211153540/http://angelodaddesio.nova100.ilsole24ore.com/2011/11/monti-ditalia-e-dargentina.html |date=11 February 2012 }} (in Italian). ''[[Il Sole 24 Ore]]''. 17 November 2011. Retrieved 30 December 2011.</ref><ref>[http://www.lanacion.com.ar/1423104-mario-monti-el-sucesor-de-berlusconi-es-hijo-de-un-argentino \"''Mario Monti, el sucesor de Berlusconi, es hijo de un argentino''\"] (in Spanish). ''[[La Naci\u00f3n]]''. 14 November 2011. Retrieved 30 December 2011.</ref> Monti's father went back to Argentina during [[World War II]], but later returned to his family home in Varese.<ref>Camanzini, Enrico. [http://www.ilgiorno.it/varese/politica/2011/11/12/618067-mario_monti_dalla_citta_giardino_palazzo_madama.shtml \"''Mario Monti, dalla citt\u00e0 giardino al Palazzo Madama: I ricordi delle gite sui monti delle Prealpi''\"] (in Italian). ''[[Il Giorno (newspaper)|Il Giorno]]''. 12 November 2011. Retrieved 17 November 2011.</ref>\n\nMonti studied at the private Leo XIII High School and attended [[Bocconi University]] of [[Milan]], where he obtained a degree in economics in 1965. Later, he won a scholarship to [[Yale University]] where he studied under [[James Tobin]], a recipient of the [[Nobel Prize in Economics]].<ref name=eucv>Public hearing: Strengthening economic governance in the EU (Brussels, 13 January 2011)&nbsp;\u2014 [http://www.europarl.europa.eu/document/activities/cont/201101/20110112ATT11575/20110112ATT11575EN.pdf Curriculum vitae of speakers]. Retrieved 12 November 2011.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/fandd/2005/06/people.htm\n|title=Super Mario and the Temple of Learning|author=Clift, Jeremy|date=June 2005|publisher=[[International Monetary Fund]]}}</ref>\n\n==Academic career==\nMonti began his academic career at the [[University of Trento]], before moving to teach economics at the [[University of Turin]] from 1970 to 1985, and finally to [[Bocconi University]], where he was appointed Rector in 1989, and President in 1994. He also served as President of the SUERF (The European Money and Finance Forum) from 1982 to 1985.<ref name=suerf>{{cite web|author=Staff|url=http://www.suerf.org/index.php?option=com_k2&view=item&id=39&Itemid=6|title=Past SUERF Presidents and Vice Presidents|date=n.d.|publisher=[[SUERF]]|accessdate=14 November 2011}}</ref> His research helped to create the \"Klein-Monti model\", aimed at describing the behaviour of banks operating under monopoly circumstances.<ref>Matthews, Kent and Thompson, John (2008). [https://www.amazon.co.uk/Economics-Banking-Kent-Matthews/dp/0470519649/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1329141708&sr=8-1#reader_0470519649 The economics of banking], Chapter 6: The Theory of the Banking Firm, pp. 77\u201391. Wiley. Retrieved 13 February 2012.</ref>\n\n==European Commissioner==\n===Santer Commission===\nIn 1994, Monti was appointed to the [[Santer Commission]], along with [[Emma Bonino]], by Prime Minister [[Silvio Berlusconi]]. In his office as a [[European Commissioner]] from 1994 to 1999, he was responsible for internal market, financial services and financial integration, customs, and taxation.<ref name=sna14nov>{{cite news|title=Ex EU Commissioner Mario Monti Takes over Italy|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Ex+EU+Commissioner+Mario+Monti+Takes+over+Italy.-a0272330733|accessdate=12 June 2013|newspaper=Sofia News Agency|date=14 November 2011}}</ref> His work with the Commission earned him the nickname \"[[Mario|Super Mario]]\" from his colleagues and from the press.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/11/11/world/europe/italy-mario-monti-profile/index.html|title=Who is Italy's 'Super Mario' Monti?|author=Smith-Spark, Laura|publisher=CNN|date=13 November 2011|accessdate=15 November 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Prodi Commission===\nIn 1999, Prime Minister [[Massimo D'Alema]] confirmed Monti's appointment to the new [[Prodi Commission]] and he was given one of the most powerful positions at the Commission, with responsibility for [[European Commissioner for Competition|Competition]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/letter_from_america/3921303.stm| title=Examining the EU executive|publisher=BBC|date=23 July 2004|accessdate=13 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nAs Competition Commissioner, Monti led the investigation into a number of high-profile and controversial mergers, including: [[Scania AB]] & [[Volvo]] (1999),<ref name=\"EuroVoice 23032000\">{{cite web| url=http://www.europeanvoice.com/article/imported/monti-puts-brakes-on-eu-merger-mania/40395.aspx|title=Monti puts brakes on EU merger mania|publisher=European Voice|date=23 March 2000|accessdate=13 February 2012}}</ref> [[MCI Inc.|WorldCom]] & [[Sprint Nextel|Sprint]] (2000),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.cnet.com/2100-1033-243110.html|title=Sprint, WorldCom call off $120 billion merger|publisher=CNet News|date=13 July 2000|accessdate=13 February 2012}}</ref> [[General Electric]] & [[Honeywell]] (2001), [[Schneider Electric]] & [[Legrand (company)|Legrand]] (2001)<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.economist.com/node/814366|title=A shocking denouement|work=The Economist|date=11 October 2001| accessdate=13 February 2012}}</ref> and [[Carnival Corporation & plc|Carnival Corporation]] & [[P&O Ferries]] (2002).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2002/jul/25/12|title=EU backs Carnival bid for P&O|newspaper=The Guardian|date=25 July 2002|accessdate=13 February 2012}}</ref> His term in office also saw the [[European Court of Justice]], for the first time, overrule the Commission's decision to block a merger in three separate cases, although two were decided by his predecessor.<ref name=\"The Full Monti\">{{cite web|url=http://news.cnet.com/The-full-Monti/2100-1016_3-5178159.html|title=The full Monti|publisher=CNet News|date=24 March 2004|accessdate=13 February 2012}}</ref> Monti was also responsible for levying the EU's largest ever fine at the time (\u20ac497 million) against [[Microsoft]] for abusing its dominant market position in 2004.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/3563697.stm|title=Microsoft hit by record EU fine|publisher=BBC|date=24 March 2004|accessdate=13 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[File:ITALY-MONTI.jpg|thumb|left|Mario Monti served as a [[European Commissioner]] from 1995 to 2004.]]\nMonti was criticised in the media and by competition lawyers for the perceived inflexibility of the merger oversight process and the high number of cases that were being blocked.<ref name=\"EuroVoice 23032000\"/><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.economist.com/node/387773|title=Spaghetti Monti|work=The Economist|date=5 October 2000|accessdate=13 February 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC 011102\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/2385037.stm|title=Mario Monti: Merger man on a mission|publisher=BBC|date=1 November 2002|accessdate=13 February 2012}}</ref> On 1 November 2002, Monti responding to the European Court of Justice's ruling which reversed his decision to block the merger between [[Airtours International Airways|Airtours]] & First Choice Holidays said, \"Last week was a tough week for the Commission's merger control policy and of course for me.\"<ref name=\"The Full Monti\"/><ref name=\"BBC 011102\"/> This ruling in combination with his decision to block the [[General Electric]] & [[Honeywell]] merger led to criticism in the United States against both the Commission's procedures and accusations that Monti's decisions were politically motivated.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.economist.com/node/905116|title=Monti braves the catcalls|work=The Economist|date=13 December 2001|accessdate=13 February 2012}}</ref>  Monti, however, was defended by supporters who saw his actions as an important step in the development of competition law in the EU. Dan Rubinfeld, economics professor at the [[University of California]] who worked on the US Justice Department's antitrust case against Microsoft, said of Monti, \"There has been a lot of talk of politics in this and other cases, but I believe he has been driven entirely by the desire to do the right thing.\"<ref name=\"The Full Monti\"/>\n\nOn 11 December 2002, Monti proposed a series of reforms to the EU's merger rules and made structural changes within the Commission's Competition department which aimed to improve transparency for companies throughout the merger review process.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.europeanvoice.com/article/imported/monti-unveils-merger-reform-proposals-based-on-us-model/46333.aspx|title=Monti unveils merger reform proposals based on US model|publisher=European Voice|date=12 December 2002|accessdate=13 February 2012}}</ref> The reforms were adopted by the EU as [[European Union merger law|Regulation 139/2004 (known as ECMR).]]\n\nIn 2004, Prime Minister [[Silvio Berlusconi]] returned to power in Italy and chose not to re-appoint Monti to the Commission when his second term ended.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-15695056|title=Profile: Mario Monti|publisher=BBC|date=13 November 2011|accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Barroso Commission===\nIn 2010, Monti was asked by Commission President [[Jos\u00e9 Manuel Barroso|Manuel Barroso]] to draft a \"Report on the Future of the Single Market\" proposing further measures towards the completion of the EU's [[single market|Single Market]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://euobserver.com/19/28856|title=Mario Monti to draw up single market report|publisher=EU Observer|date=21 October 2009|accessdate=13 February 2012}}</ref><ref>[http://ec.europa.eu/bepa/pdf/monti_report_final_10_05_2010_en.pdf Report on the future of the Single Market], 2010</ref>  The published report, adopted by the EU on 13 April 2011, proposed 12 reforms to the Single Market and was intended to \"give new momentum\" to the European economy.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://europa.eu/rapid/pressReleasesAction.do?reference=IP/11/469|title=Twelve projects for the 2012 Single Market: together for new growth|publisher=European Commission|date=13 April 2011|accessdate=13 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Prime Minister of Italy==\n\n===Appointment===\n[[File:Monti Cabinet with Giorgio Napolitano.jpg|thumb|right|Monti's Cabinet swearing-in ceremony at the presence of [[President of Italy|President]] [[Giorgio Napolitano|Napolitano]].]]\n\nOn 9 November 2011, Monti was appointed a [[Senator for life|lifetime senator]] by [[President of Italy|Italian President]] [[Giorgio Napolitano]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Napolitano nomina Monti senatore a vita|url=http://www.corriere.it/politica/11_novembre_09/mario-monti-senatore-a-vita_87ba0e7c-0aff-11e1-8371-eb51678ca784.shtml|accessdate=9 November 2011|newspaper=[[Corriere della Sera]]|date=9 November 2011}}</ref> He was seen as a favourite to replace Silvio Berlusconi to lead a new unity government in Italy in order to implement reforms and austerity measures.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mario Monti Emerges as Favorite To Lead Italy|date=10 November 2011|first1=Giselda|last1=Vagnoni|first2=Catherine|last2=Hornby| agency=Reuters |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/11/10/us-italy-idUSTRE7A72NG20111110|accessdate=10 November 2011}}</ref> On 12 November 2011, following Berlusconi's resignation, Napolitano invited Monti to form a new government.<ref>{{cite news|title=Incarico a Monti: \"Occorre crescita ed equit\u00e0\"|url=http://www.repubblica.it/politica/2011/11/13/news/monti_napolitano_dopo_incarico-24963634/?ref=HREA-1|accessdate=12 November 2011|newspaper=[[la Repubblica]]|date=12 November 2011}}</ref> Monti accepted the offer, and held talks with the leaders of the main Italian political parties, declaring that he wanted to form a government that would remain in office until the next scheduled general elections in 2013.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/17/world/europe/monti-forms-new-italian-government.html|title=Facing Crisis, Technocrats Take Charge in Italy|date=16 November 2011|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=16 November 2011|first1=Rachel|last1=Donadio|first2=Elisabetta|last2=Povoledo}}</ref> On 16 November 2011, Monti was sworn in as [[Prime Minister of Italy]], after unveiling a [[technocracy|technocratic]] [[Monti Cabinet|cabinet]] composed entirely of unelected [[professional]]s.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-15751179 \"Monti Unveils Technocratic Cabinet for Italy\"] (16 November 2011). [[BBC News]]. Retrieved 17 November 2011.</ref> He also chose to hold the post of [[List of Italian Ministers of Economy and Finances|Minister of Economy and Finances]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/financialcrisis/8894014/Mario-Monti-appoints-himself-economy-minister-as-he-unveils-Italy-government.html|title=Mario Monti Appoints Himself Economy Minister as He Unveils Italy Government|date= 16 November 2011|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|accessdate=16 November 2011|first=Nick|last=Squires}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-15751179|title=Monti Unveils Technocratic Cabinet for Italy|date=16 November 2011|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=17 November 2011}}</ref> On 17 and 18 November 2011, the [[Italian Senate]] and [[Italian Chamber of Deputies]] both passed motions of confidence supporting Monti's government, with only [[Lega Nord]] voting against.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/italian-leader-mario-monti-wins-second-confidence-vote-6264222.html|title=Italian leader Mario Monti wins second confidence vote|work=The Independent|date=18 November 2011|accessdate=10 February 2012|author=Winfield, Nicole}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/11/17/us-italy-idUSTRE7AA2GC20111117|title=New Italy PM wins confidence vote on tough reform plans|work=Reuters|date=17 November 2011|accessdate=13 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Austerity measures===\nOn 4 December 2011, Monti's government introduced emergency austerity measures intended to stem the worsening economic conditions in Italy and restore market confidence, especially after rising [[European sovereign debt crisis#Italy|Italian government bond yields]] began to threaten Italy's financial stability.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-11-28/italy-set-for-a-sizeable-cost-increase-at-8-billion-euro-bond-auction.html| title=Europe Italy Bonds.Italy Pays More Than 7% at Treasury-Bond Auction for Third Time in a Week|newspaper=Bloomberg| date=29 November 2011|accessdate=10 February 2012}}</ref> The austerity package called for increased taxes, pension reform and measures to fight tax evasion. Monti also announced that he would be giving up his own salary as part of the reforms.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-16024316|title=Italy crisis: Mario Monti announces austerity plan |publisher=BBC|date=4 December 2011|accessdate=10 February 2012}}</ref> On 16 December 2011, the [[Italian Chamber of Deputies|Lower House of the Italian Parliament]] adopted the measures by a vote of 495 to 88.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-16212405|title=Italy's Monti wins confidence vote over austerity|publisher=BBC|date=16 December 2011|accessdate=10 February 2012}}</ref> Six days later the [[Italian Senate|Upper House]] gave final approval to the package by a vote of 257 to 41.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-16301956|title=Italy senate passes Monti's austerity package|publisher=BBC|date=22 December 2011|accessdate=10 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Labour market reforms===\n[[File:Secretary Clinton Meets With Italian Prime Minister Monti (6830102155).jpg|thumb|Prime Minister Monti with [[U.S. Secretary of State]] [[Hillary Clinton]], 2012.]]\n\nOn 20 January 2012, Monti's government formally adopted a package of reforms targeting Italy's labour market. The reforms are intended to open certain professions (such as taxi drivers, pharmacists, doctors, lawyers and notaries) to more competition by reforming their licensing systems and abolishing minimum tariffs for their services.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-16653863|title=Italy approves sweeping reforms|publisher=BBC News|date=20 January 2012 |accessdate=13 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/b13df170-4392-11e1-adda-00144feab49a.html#axzz1mFlcNTKs|title=Monti unveils liberalisation plans|newspaper=Financial Times|date=20 January 2012| accessdate=13 February 2012}}</ref>  Article 18 of Italy's labour code, which requires companies that employ 15 or more workers to re-hire (rather than compensate) any employee found to have been fired without just cause,<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.economist.com/node/1205271|title=Berlusconi 2, Cofferati 1|newspaper=The Economist|date=27 June 2002| accessdate=13 February 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Reuters 020212\">{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/02/02/us-italy-reforms-idUSTRE8111TF20120202|title=Italy govt to pass labour reforms even without unions|publisher=Reuters|date=2 February 2012|accessdate=13 February 2012}}</ref> would also be reformed. The reforms to Article 18 are intended to make it easier for companies to dismiss or lay-off employees, which would hopefully encourage companies to hire more employees on permanent rather than short-term renewable contracts.<ref name=\"Reuters 020212\"/> The proposals have been met by strong opposition from labour unions and public protests.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://business.financialpost.com/2011/12/27/italy-vs-the-unions/|title=Italy vs the unions|newspaper=Financial Post|date=27 December 2011|accessdate=13 February 2012}}</ref> In early January 2012, consultations between the government and labour unions commenced<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.france24.com/en/20120109-italy-begins-talks-labour-market-reform |title=Italy begins talks on labour market reform |newspaper=France 24 |date=9 January 2012 |accessdate=13 February 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120731201449/http://www.france24.com/en/20120109-italy-begins-talks-labour-market-reform |archivedate=31 July 2012 }}</ref> and on 13 February it was reported in the Italian media that a compromise on the proposals was very close and the government was hopeful that reforms could be approved by the Italian parliament in March.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.repubblica.it/politica/2012/02/13/news/riforma_articolo_18-29782507/?ref=HREC1-42|title=E il Professore accelera sulla riforma|newspaper=La Repubblica|date=13 February 2012|accessdate=13 February 2012}}</ref>{{Update after|2012|03|15|reason=Check to see if Italian parliament has approved reforms}}\n\n===2013 election===\nOn 21 December 2012, Monti announced his resignation as Prime Minister, having made a public promise to step down on 8 December, after the passing of the 2013 Budget.<ref>[[The Economist]] - Dec 9th 2012 by J.H. | ROME - Mario Monti's resignation\n[https://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/14/world/europe/mario-monti-asked-to-form-a-new-government-in-italy.html]</ref> He initially stated that he would only remain in office until [[2013 Italian general election|an early election]] could be held.<ref>{{cite web|title=Italy's Mario Monti set to resign as MPs pass budget|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-20814796#TWEET467092|publisher=BBC|accessdate=21 December 2012}}</ref> However, on 28 December, he announced that he would seek to remain Prime Minister by contesting the election, as the leader of a centrist coalition, the [[Civic Choice]].\n\nThe election was held on 24 February 2013, and Monti's centrist coalition was only able to come fourth, with 10.5% of the vote. Monti remained Prime Minister until a coalition was formed on 28 April led by [[Enrico Letta]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/world/2013/04/27/italy_gets_unusual_leftright_coalition_government_with_enrico_letta_as_pm.html|title=Italy gets unusual left-right coalition government with Enrico Letta as PM|newspaper=Toronto Star|date=27 April 2013|accessdate=3 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\n===Senator for life===\n[[File:Dmitry Medvedev and Mario Monti 20 May 2012.jpeg|thumb|right|Mario Monti with Russian Prime Minister [[Dmitry Medvedev]] at the [[38th G8 summit]].]]\nOn 9 November 2011,  Monti was appointed a lifetime senator by Italian President [[Giorgio Napolitano]], in accordance with the second paragraph of \"Article 59 of the Constitution, which merits national honor distinguished in science and society\". He was a member of the Commission for Industry, Commerce and Tourism from 30 November 2011 to 14 March 2013 in the sixteenth legislature. Monti was a member of the independents' mixed parliamentary group until 19 March 2013, when he joined the [[Civic Choice]] (SC) parliamentary group, becoming the first lifetime senator aligned with a party group. On 7 May 2013, he became a member of the Commission for Foreign Affairs and Emigration.\n\n===President of Civic Choice===\nOn 4 January 2013, Monti launched Civic Choice as an electoral list of the civil society, to realize the implementation of his agenda in a future government. SC was announced as part of the [[With Monti for Italy]] (CMI) centrist coalition, alongside [[Union of the Centre (2002)|Union of the Centre]] (UdC) and [[Future and Freedom]] (FLI). In the 2013 general election, the party obtained 8.3% of the vote, 37 deputies (on own lists) and 15 senators (within CMI). On 12 March 2013, Civic Choice was turned into a political party as Monti took office as acting SC president in the Provisional Committee of the party and appointed senator [[Andrea Olivero]] as provisional political coordinator. On 16 May 2013, Mario Monti was unanimously elected president of the Civic Choice.\n\nOn 17 October 2013 he resigned and was replaced by his deputy Alberto Bombassei as acting president.<ref>[http://www.repubblica.it/politica/2013/10/17/news/monti_si_dimette_da_scelta_civica_11_senatori_contro_di_me_per_legge_stabilit-68830684 Monti si dimette da Scelta Civica: \"11 senatori pi\u00f9 Mauro mi hanno sfiduciato\"]/</ref> Monti cited his disagreement with 12 senators (out of 20), including [[Mario Mauro]], [[Andrea Olivero]], [[Gabriele Albertini]], [[Pier Ferdinando Casini]] (UdC leader), Maria Paola Merloni, Luigi Marino and Lucio Romano. Particularly, Monti criticized Mauro's line of unconditioned support to the government and of transforming SC in a larger [[centre-right]] political party, open to [[The People of Freedom]].<ref name=Corriere-2013-10-19>{{cite web|url=http://www.corriere.it/politica/13_ottobre_19/monti-casini-mauro-specialisti-slalom-senza-me-berlusconi-sarebbe-colle-bbb58a76-387a-11e3-a22e-23aa40bc2aa7.shtml |title=\u00abHo imbarcato specialisti di slalom Senza me Berlusconi sarebbe sul Colle|work=Corriere|accessdate=5 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sceltacivica.it/doc/1071/mario-monti-si-dimette-da-scelta-civica.htm |title=Mario Monti si dimette da Scelta Civica|work=Scelta Civica per l'Italia|accessdate=5 December 2013}}</ref><ref name=Corriere-2013-10-18>[http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/2013/ottobre/18/rivolta_suoi_senatori_Monti_co_0_20131018_a931e9a2-37b8-11e3-a78c-01d0d3671c7b.shtml ]{{dead link|date=December 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Other activities==\nMonti actively participates in several major [[think tanks]]. He was the founding chairman of [[Bruegel (institution)|Bruegel]], another European think tank, which was formed in 2005. \n\nMonti is a leading member of the exclusive [[Bilderberg Group]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bilderbergmeetings.org/governance.html |title=Steering Committee |publisher=[[Bilderberg Group|Bilderberg Meetings]] |accessdate=12 November 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111109000703/http://www.bilderbergmeetings.org/governance.html |archivedate=9 November 2011 }}</ref> He has also been an international advisor to [[Goldman Sachs]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/analysis-and-features/what-price-the-new-democracy-goldman-sachs-conquers-europe-6264091.html|title=What Price the New Democracy? Goldman Sachs Conquers Europe|last=Foley|first=Stephen|date=18 November 2011|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=18 November 2011}}</ref> and [[The Coca-Cola Company]].<ref>European Commission{{spaced ndash}}Economic and Financial Affairs. Brussels Economic Forum 2009, speakers: [http://ec.europa.eu/economy_finance/bef2009/speakers/mario-monti/index.html \"Mario Monti\"]. Retrieved 19 November 2011.</ref> \n\nIn 2007, Monti was one of the first supporters of the first European civic forum, \u00c9tats G\u00e9n\u00e9raux de l'Europe, initiated by European [[think tank]] [[EuropaNova]] and [[European Movement]]. He was also a member of the French government's [[Jacques Attali|Attali Commission]] from 2007 to 2008,<ref name=eucv/><ref>{{Interlanguage link multi|Commission Attali|fr|3=Commission pour la lib\u00e9ration de la croissance fran\u00e7aise}}</ref> appointed by [[Nicolas Sarkozy]] to provide recommendations to enhance economic growth in France.\n\nMonti is a founding member of the [[Spinelli Group]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pr.euractiv.com/press-release/mep-spinelli-group-launched-today-european-parliament-16109|title=MEP Spinelli Group launched today in European Parliament|work=EurActiv PR}}</ref> an organization launched in September 2010 to facilitate integration within the European Union (other members of the steering group include [[Jacques Delors]], [[Daniel Cohn-Bendit]], [[Guy Verhofstadt]], [[Andrew Duff]] and [[Elmar Brok]]).\n\nIn January 2014, Monti became Chairman of the High Level Group on Own Resources, a consultative committee of the European Union aimed at proposing new forms of revenue for the European Union's budget. The final report of the group was adopted in December 2016 and published in January 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ec.europa.eu/budget/mff/hlgor/library/reports-communication/20170120-notedetransmission-hlgor-final-report.pdf|title=Monti report recommends reform of EU budget|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref> It argued for new tax sources, such as on carbon and fuel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ec.europa.eu/budget/mff/hlgor/library/reports-communication/hlgor-report_20170104.pdf|title=Future Financing of the EU - Final report and recommendations of the High Level Group on Own Resources|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Monti chaired a search committee which recommended to the European Commission the appointment of [[Mauro Ferrari]] as the next President of the [[European Research Council]] (ERC).<ref>[https://ec.europa.eu/commission/presscorner/detail/en/IP_19_2471 Commission appoints Mauro Ferrari as next President of the European Research Council] [[European Commission]], press release of May 14, 2019.</ref>\n\nOther activities include: \n* [[European Investment Bank]] (EIB), Member of the Appointment Advisory Committee<ref>[https://www.eib.org/en/about/governance-and-structure/statutory-bodies/board_of_governors/appointment-advisory-committee/index.htm Appointment Advisory Committee] [[European Investment Bank]] (EIB).</ref>\n* [[Friends of Europe]], Member of the Praesidium  \n* [[Moody's]], Member of the Senior European Advisory Council<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sternalumni.nyu.edu/s/1068/GroupBus/3col.aspx?sid=1068&gid=2&verbiagebuilder=1&pgid=1008|title=NYU SternConnect - Speaker Profile|work=nyu.edu}}</ref> \n* [[Atlantic Council]], Member of the Business and Economics Advisors Group<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.acus.org/people/beag|title=Advisory Groups|author=Jason Harmala|work=Atlantic Council|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120106072611/http://www.acus.org/people/beag|archivedate=6 January 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Transparency International]], Chairman of the European Advisory Board (since 2015)<ref>[https://transparency.eu/advisory-board/ Our Advisory Board] [[Transparency International]].</ref>\n* [[Trilateral Commission]], European Chairman (-2011)<ref name=trilateral>{{cite web|url=http://www.trilateral.org/go.cfm?do=Page.View&pid=11 |title=About the Trilateral Commission - European Region |publisher=[[Trilateral Commission]] |accessdate=3 April 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130509143411/http://www.trilateral.org/go.cfm?do=Page.View&pid=11 |archivedate=9 May 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSince 1970 Monti has been married to Elsa Antonioli (born 1944),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blitzquotidiano.it/politica-italiana/monti-secchione-padre-uberto-ceroni-1114152/|title=Monti 'non-era un secchione': parla Padre Uberto Ceroni, suo ex prof|publisher=Blitz|date=10 February 2012|accessdate=10 February 2012|language=Italian}}</ref> an [[Italian Red Cross]] volunteer, with whom he has two children, Federica and Giovanni.<ref>{{cite web|title='Mario Monti il professore riservato ma intransigente dallo humour anglosassone'|url=http://www.adnkronos.com/mobile/Politica/news/Mario-Monti-il-professore-riservato-ma-intransigente-dallo-humour-anglosassone_3.1.2642191336.php|publisher=[[Adnkronos]]|accessdate=14 November 2011|language=Italian |date=13 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nKnown for his reserved character, Monti acknowledges not being especially sociable.<ref name=france-presse>{{cite news|agency=Agence France-Presse|title=Reserved Mario Monti Has Little in Common with Colourful Silvio Berlusconi|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/2011/11/13/reserved-mario-monti-has-little-in-common-with-silvio-berlusconi/|newspaper= [[National Post]]|date=13 November 2011|accessdate=21 November 2011}}</ref> He said that his youth was given over to hard study; spare-time activities included cycling and keeping up with world affairs by tuning into foreign short-wave radio stations.<ref name=france-presse/>\n\nIn addition to his native Italian, Monti also speaks English.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mario Monti Says It Is Wrong to Under-Valuate Market Reaction to Italy Program |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=A-TrcwBsKVQ |website=YouTube |publisher= Bloomberg Markets and Finance |accessdate=21 Nov 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title= Interview With Mario Monti {{!}} TIME |url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OIjfl983Tag |website=YouTube |publisher=TIME |accessdate= 21 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title= Mario Monti Doesn't See a Danger of Italy Leaving the Eurozone |url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hUhFEthU2RM |website=YouTube |publisher=Bloomberg Politics |accessdate= 21 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and decorations==\n{|\n|-\n|[[File:ITA OMRI 2001 GC BAR.svg|80px]]\n|[[Order of Merit of the Italian Republic|Knight Grand Cross of the Order of Merit of the Italian Republic]] \u2013 awarded on 29 November 2004<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.quirinale.it/elementi/DettaglioOnorificenze.aspx?decorato=144247 |title=Presidential Awards |publisher=[[Quirinal Palace]] |accessdate=19 November 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120113141549/http://www.quirinale.it/elementi/DettaglioOnorificenze.aspx?decorato=144247 |archivedate=13 January 2012 }}</ref>\n|-\n|[[File:Commendatore OMRI BAR.svg|80px]]\n|[[Order of Merit of the Italian Republic|Commander of the Order of Merit of the Italian Republic]] \u2013 awarded on 27 December 1992<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.quirinale.it/elementi/DettaglioOnorificenze.aspx?decorato=195207 |title=Presidential Awards |publisher=[[Quirinal Palace]] |accessdate=19 November 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120113141514/http://www.quirinale.it/elementi/DettaglioOnorificenze.aspx?decorato=195207 |archivedate=13 January 2012 }}</ref>\n|-\n|[[File:JPN Kyokujitsu-sho 1Class BAR.svg|80px|ribbon bar]]\n|Grand Cordon of the [[Order of the Rising Sun]] \u2013 awarded on 3 November 2015\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Prime Ministers of Italy]]\n*[[Monti Cabinet]]\n*[[Monti's Agenda for Italy]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/silvio-berlusconi/8881761/Mario-Monti-profile-of-Super-Mario.html Profile of Mario Monti] at ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]''\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/world/mario-monti Articles about Monti] at ''[[The Guardian]]''\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-aca}}\n{{s-bef|before=Luigi Guatri}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Rector (academia)|Rector]] of [[Bocconi University]]|years=1989\u20131994}}\n{{s-aft|after=Roberto Ruozi}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Giovanni Spadolini]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=President of [[Bocconi University]]|years=1994\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-civ}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Peter Sutherland]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=European Group Chairman of the [[Trilateral Commission]] |years=2010\u20132011}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jean-Claude Trichet]]}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|